The Oyo State House of Assembly is set to determine the fate of Deputy Governor Rauf Olaniyan. Chairman of the House Committee on Information Kazeem Olayanju, who confirmed the receipt of Olaniyan’s response to the petitions against him, said the deputy governor responded before the expiration of the seven days ultimatum given him. He added that the impeachment process will continue next week when plenary resumes. “Yes, the deputy governor has responded. Our next plenary sitting will be next Wednesday and the process will continue then,” Olayanju said in a message. It was gathered that the lawmakers are currently attending a seminar organised for lawmakers from Lagos, Ogun, Ondo and Oyo states.   Adamu to campaign council: Osun is a must-win     Lagos inaugurates floating clinic for riverine communities     Oyebanji, Afuye get Certificates of Return   The Assembly yesterday approved Governor Seyi Makinde’s request to access additional N2 billion loan from Fidelity Bank Plc. The Speaker, Adebo Ogundoyin, noted that it was imperative and expedient for the government to fulfil its own part of the agreement to ensure a speedy completion of the projects. The letter reads: “To further complement the government’s efforts on the provision of critical and iconic infrastructure, and very laudable projects, the Executive Council is seeking approval of the House of Assembly to access additional N2 billion facility to provide counterpart funding to complete donor assisted projects. “The facility is to be accessed from Fidelity Bank Plc, at a concessional interest rate of 12 per cent per annum with a repayment period of 12 months, and management fees of 0.25 per cent one-off.” The projects include Nigeria COVID-19 Action Recovery and Economic Stimulus; Accelerating Nutrition Results Project in Nigeria; Ibadan Urban Flood Management Project; Better Education Service Delivery for All and the UBEC/SUBEB 2021 Matching Grant.